english:
  title: Biography of Jeong Hyeon-suk of Cho-gye
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In Cho-gye there lived a recluse gentleman named Jeong Sang-sa, who passed the state examination in the same year as my father, Ga-jeong-gong. He had a son called Seup-in, whose courtesy name was Hyeon-suk. I had known his face for a long time, yet we never shared warm and cordial moments together, and I did not even know he was the son of Sang-sa. Hyeon-suk himself never mentioned it. He possessed will and spirit, talent and brilliance. When wine loosened his tongue, he spoke freely without restraint, which made his colleagues fear him.

    In the spring of the Eul-mi year, Yi Sichung of Iksan and An Jeong-dang of Juk-gye became examiners of the civil service. Hyeon-suk's policy essay received top marks. He was appointed to teach at the National Academy, and through his merit was promoted to participate in court office. He neither blindly followed others nor compromised his principles. All the officials wished to befriend him closely, yet Hyeon-suk regarded them with utter indifference.

    When selected to govern Yeongju, he was about to take office when the clerks, following ancient custom, requested that he proceed to the Temple of Disaster-Prevention to burn incense. Hyeon-suk replied: "A minister does not transgress against propriety. From whence comes disaster? If it comes unbidden, a gentleman simply accepts it with equanimity. Before sickness arises, I attend to my health; when it comes, I use medicine. When death approaches, if the organs are already failing beyond remedy, what use is a Disaster-Prevention Temple to me?" He ordered the clerks to remove it.

    Some said it was later cut up to make a mat. This was the storyteller's exaggeration. There was a pagoda in the province. Hyeon-suk inquired its name. The clerks told him it was called the Pagoda of No-Trust. "Is this true?" asked Hyeon-suk. "How dare we deceive you," they replied. He asked among the local gentlemen and elders living in retirement, and all confirmed it. Hyeon-suk exclaimed: "How strange! We do not rest beneath a tree of evil name, nor drink from a spring called Robber's Spring—why? Because we despise the name. Yet how can there stand so lofty a form, observed by all the people of a county, bearing the name 'No-Trust'? Remove grain, and people cannot live; remove weapons, and they cannot defend themselves—yet we would sooner abandon grain and arms like worn-out sandals than abandon trust. This my master Confucius has already spoken."

    He ordered the provincial officials to set a date and demolish it, using its bricks to repair the official guesthouse.

    It happened that a powerful minister held sway and was excessively devoted to Buddhism. He sought to destroy Hyeon-suk, but courtiers took pity on his integrity and many spoke to the ruler on his behalf. Thus he was spared, and his reputation grew even greater.

    After the minister fell from power and met his end, Hyeon-suk was again employed, governing first Yangju, then Milseong. Wherever he went, he suppressed the strong and aided the weak, showing both authority and benevolence. To forbid heterodox shrines and punish shamans was Hyeon-suk's customary work, which I shall not detail. When he came to the capital as an official of the ministry, he refused to offer sacrifices to the local earth deity and wished to eliminate the Disaster-Prevention Temple, but his lowly position prevented it.

    When his mother died, Hyeon-suk kept vigil at her tomb for three years, and did the same for his father. At his profound sorrow, all praised him. Truly, loyal ministers come from the house of filial sons.

    When the present ruler succeeded to office, he hastened to seek talented men. The Prime Minister had long esteemed Hyeon-suk's reputation, and recommended him for appointment as Director of Compilation—equivalent to the position of Keeper of the Imperial Library. He was granted the robes of the third rank, a great honor. But then he received orders to undertake a mission to Japan.

    All who knew Hyeon-suk feared for him, and his son, who this year became the top graduate in the civil service examination, wept toward heaven so bitterly that all who heard pitied him beyond measure. Yet Hyeon-suk remained calm, and righteousness showed upon his face as he spoke:

    "To live is to die—why should I choose where? I am a subject with a sovereign—how can I refuse his calling? Moreover, my ambition is to accomplish service; even to a foreign land I shall not hesitate. How much less, when the East is known as the land where gentlemen do not perish? And now, when friendship between two kingdoms is newly begun and they greet each other with joy? Yet hindrances still remain between us. In my going, I shall resolve them completely.

    "As for the Master's thought of taking a raft, the traces of one gathering herbs, and the tales of the Cloud Emperor and the Pheasant Records—these I shall detail for you all. On this I give my word."

    Thereupon all competed to compose poems and songs to present him at the farewell feast outside the city. Being bound by our families' long friendship, I could not remain silent. I have therefore gathered and arranged this account based on what Yi Ho-yeon has said. Ho-yeon is a man of substance whose words are not false.

    He also reported: "When keeping vigil at his father's tomb, since his father loved Buddhism, Hyeon-suk read Buddhist sutras daily until he had memorized them, and retained them long afterward. Such is how a filial son cannot bear that his parent should cease to exist."

    One day, visiting a friend, that household happened to be performing a Buddhist rite with a monk. The monk was reciting several sutras when Hyeon-suk, standing nearby, recited them fluently along with him. The monk assumed he must be a Buddhist believer and asked his name. Hyeon-suk promptly replied: "I am none other than Jeong So-and-so, who demolished the pagoda." The whole assembly burst into great laughter, marveling at his prodigious memory.

    When a Japanese envoy asked the palace escort what manner of man Hyeon-suk was, the escort answered truthfully. The Japanese envoy, being a Buddhist, feared his uncompromising integrity. He immediately said: "One who rejects the Buddha cannot be recognized by our law. We request another in his stead." And thus Hyeon-suk was not sent after all.
