    - The Eul-mi year (乙未年) refers to 1355 in the Korean calendar, during the Goryeo period.
    - The phrase 'gentleman does not perish' (君子不死之國) reflects the Confucian valuation of the Korean peninsula as a land of virtue and moral rectitude.
    - '''Robber''s Spring'' (盜泉) and the ''evil tree'' are Confucian moral exemplars—the virtuous avoid places and things with ignoble associations, demonstrating that reputation and name carry moral weight.'
    - The Master's 'taking a raft' alludes to Confucius's contemplation of leaving civilization when it declined.
    - This anecdote about the Buddhist recitation displays the Confucian ideal of mastery through devotion to duty rather than belief.
